    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_406126">One of my old DMs spawned a series of adventures and campaigns based solely on the player's desire to create magical items. Our group was the &quot;Oh that's a bad ass monster we just killed, lets carve off some body parts and see what we can make out of it&quot; kind of group. Displacer Cloaks, Dragon-scale whatevers, weapons created from monster appendages.......all of these gave us a reason to adventure, either to do the creating mage a favor in return for the work, or to collect more reagents which themselves were extremely rare/dangerous to acquire. <br />
<br />
I'm getting bitched at by my players right now because i'm not giving them enough magic items. I think its been 3 adventures now since they've been able to lay their hands on one. I personally prefer that method because it makes them appreciate the stuff they get more when it does show up. <br />
<br />
I do also like having people who <i>might</i> have magic items for sale, but I like making players actually go out and search for said vendors, and I like charging exorbitant prices for them. (A +1 weapon of anything should not start any lower than 1k gold in my book). Wizards and Priests capable of making stuff do not set up shop and do not take orders as a matter of course, and there are no &quot;Magical Item Sellers&quot; by trade in my world.<br />
<br />
There are very few situations where <i>magical items</i> MUST be part of the adventure for the PCs to survive. Any magical item effect can usually be duplicated effectively by the appropriate level wizard/priest/druid spell. Yes, they must memorize (or use spell points, whatever edition you are playing) spell slots to make it work for the party, instead of fireball, invisibility, and cure XXXX wounds. Such is adventuring though. The create food and water spell solves 1/2 of their problems right there to begin with.<br />
<br />
If you don't want your players cheesing out the environmental hazards of your game, don't make magical items that solve their problems for them available.<br />
<br />
And Cao makes a good point about making their own. Making magical items is serious business. You need peace, quiet, and all the available materials on hand when you start. That's not anything you should reasonably be able to do while adventuring, let alone adventuring in the Underdark of all places. The 2nd ed. handbook puts the time for even minor item creation at 1 month+.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
<br>
