    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_406159">I've identified your problem.<br />
<br />
Giving players a wealth of crap as they start out a new adventure is a recipe for headaches as a GM. Your problem may not be Rings of Sustenance, it could be that all your characters have gauntlets of ogre strength and do base +8 damage on their damage rolls, and they mow through creatures like they are cutting wheat. Or they could all fish up rings of invisibility and just ignore 1/2 of your encounters. Or what have you. I gave up on letting players have magical items either randomly generated at character creation, or moderated by myself. In the end introducing them to game with that much power created balance issues. Adding one magical item to an adventure, or one follower, or one friendly NPC, modifies balance a little bit. You do the next session, notice the balance has shifted, and correct a little bit. But dropping that amount of wealth on players, and basically letting them look through magical items and go &quot;I want that one, how much&quot;, is going to make balance a nightmare, in my opinion. Letting players <i>pick</i> their magic items is never a good idea. Not only does it cheapen the whole mystique and awesomeness of magic items, but it leads right to twinkery and min/maxing. <br />
<br />
Basic equipment at level 1 costs around 50g. You're giving them enough gold theoretically for 9th level characters at least. By 9th level, rings of sustenance and other high powered magical items are the norm. It sounds like you want them to have a high level experience while setting low level expectations for what they will get and have. Those two don't really jive. Especially when you give them 50k. <br />
<br />
To each their own though. I've run &quot;Power games&quot; where people got magical items right out of the box, and all I found was that it was a challenge to make the adventure threatening without outright killing players, aging them, draining their levels, or generally throwing the nastiest parts of the Monstrous Manual at them. For one shots, it can be some good zany, Hackmaster type fun. But for an adventure/campaign that desires a sense of pacing, I think you're setting yourself up to be frustrated by the power levels of your PCs.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
