    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_406339"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">People don't know their class well and are gimped, plus take forever during gameplay to figure out what the 'right' response is to a given scenario.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>We have two of these guys in our group, the rest of my players are veterans. One guy will re-read the priest or wizard section of spells constantly throughout combat, and we still wait a minute or two per round for him to decide what he wants to do. If you do have any new players to your game, it does make doing high level adventures a little tedious. <br />
<br />
Either that or they tend to take a really long time to make some relatively simple decisions, or they aren't really informed of their options, and don't do something when you as the GM kind of planned on them doing it. (Casting fireball at the appropriate time, combat healing, hold person, ect...). <br />
<br />
Casters are arguably the roughest class for new players, because it takes familiarity with lots of spells to make a good (or at least a timely) caster. That's really only something you pick up reading the spell lists frequently in your leisure time (as opposed to in the heat of combat, where you're not really trying to understand each given spell's utility), having played a lot, or being exposed to other experienced players applying the right spells at the right times.<br />
<br />
<br />
Back on the main topic, I'm a fan of expecting my adventurers to be prepared, or suffer the consequences when I decide to ask &quot;So, how much food and water do you guys have?&quot; We try to regularly do encumbrance and consumables audits to keep our players mindful that there are other, less fun but still important rules that add to the game. Besides, it can be a great excuse for a sidebar, impromptu adventure when they discover they have no food, and need to go scrounge, kill, or steal to feed themselves.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
