    <div align="left" id="post_message_406401"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">3) You get a mix of 1 and 2 such that part of the party is having fun overpowering content while the other part is sulking because they don't get to do anything.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Man, we had a campaign get like that and everyone started at level 1. Just later on, some people had characters that were pretty disgusting at combat and some people just never applied themselves.<br />
<br />
My #1 piece of advice on magic items-<br />
<br />
Never allow a magic item to come into your campaign without your approval.<br />
<br />
This means, if you're allowing them a budget for magic items, feel free to veto choices. Never allow a random roll to unbalance your campaign (ie, don't use em. Place treasure based on value but don't resort to random tables).<br />
<br />
My #2 piece of advice-<br />
<br />
Never be afraid to take something away<br />
<br />
If you've allowed a combination of skills, feats, or a specific magic item to come into the game, and it's not working out the way you expected (In a negative fashion), the good of the campaign &gt; the players feelings.<br />
<br />
Adventurers are constant targets for the unscrupulous, as they're usually well geared.</div>
